<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06183198 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06183198 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  JAPAN; US; STOCK; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Japan's central bank, seeking to stimulate the economy by reversing alongstanding inflation-fighting policy of tight credit, today lowered thediscount rate by half a percentage point to 5.5 percent.;    The cut in itslending rate to commercial banks, the first since February 1987, took effectimmediately. It triggered a sharp rally on the Tokyo stock market, where theleading indicator jumped 3.51 percent.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JAPAN CUTS KEY RATE; STOCKS JUMP  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Chart attached at end of article  </MEMO><TEXT>     In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average surged 19.23 points to2,925.98 in the first half-hour of trading.;    &quot;Today's decision was made inorder to continue sustaining steady growth led by domestic demands whilemaintaining price stability,&quot; the Bank of Japan said.;    The bank had boostedthe discount rate five times since May 1989, when it rose from 2.5 percent to3.25 percent.;    The higher rates ended an era of easy credit that helpedfuel a robust expansion of the Japanese economy and facilitated massiveoverseas investment.;    But the economy, which grew at 5.7 percent in thefiscal year that ended March 31, is expected to slow to 3.8 percent growththis year.;    &quot;It was high time for the bank to act in lowering its keylending rate,&quot; said Hirokazu Kawai, a senior economist at Nikko ResearchCenter. &quot;If it had failed to do so now, there was a possibility of a quicklyworsening economic slowdown.&quot;;    Kenneth Courtis, senior economist atDeutsche Bank Group in Tokyo, said the move was needed to prevent a &quot;verysharp fall&quot; in capital investment, which is a main engine driving theeconomy.;    He also said the rate reduction was designed to restoreconfidence in the market after the debacle of the preceding week, when thepresidents of two huge brokerages resigned because of a widening scandal intoshady dealings.;    The questionable practices include offering hugecompensation to favored clients for investment losses and deals linked toorganized crime.;    Economists said the move would be welcome in Washington,which does not want to see recession spread to any other Westernindustrialized countries. Kawai said Japan would have come under pressure toreduce interest rates at the London summit of industrialized nations July 15.;   In its statement explaining the rate cut, the Bank of Japan said&quot;inflationary pressures have been somewhat alleviated.&quot;;    Land prices inparticular have eased -- falling as much as 30 percent in some major cities --after spiraling upward during the speculative 1980s.;    And despite a severelabor shortage, nationwide wage negotiations in May led to only moderateincreases.; THE MARKETS; In trading    today:; ...; The Dow Jones average rose19.23 points by 10 a.m. EDT.; ...; August crude fell nine cents to $20.47 abarrel.; ...; In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.31 yen to 137.84 yen.; ...; InZurich, gold was $368.60 an ounce, up 20  cents.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Tokyo  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910701  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  22D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  467  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday July 1, 199100183198,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>